<DOC><DOCNO> WSJ880608-0003 </DOCNO><HL> U.S. Debt Rose At Slower Pace In First Quarter </HL><SO> </SO><IN> ECO EMI </IN><DATELINE> WASHINGTON  </DATELINE><TEXT>   Debt of U.S. households, governments and nonfinancial businesses grew at a seasonally adjusted 8.4% annual rate in the first quarter, compared to a 10.3% growth rate in the previous quarter, the Federal Reserve Board said.    New borrowing in the first quarter was at a $692.9 billion annual rate, compared to an $832.2 billion rate in the fourth quarter.    Total debt owed at the end of March was $8.452 trillion, of which $2.018 trillion, or 23%, was owed by the federal government.    The Fed's policy-making Open Market Committee has set a 7%-to-11% target range for 1988 growth in total debt, excluding that of financial institutions. This measure of debt grew by 8.8% in 1987, 12.2% in 1986 and 14.3% in 1985.    The Fed said borrowing by the federal government grew at an 11.9% annual rate in the first quarter, compared with a 10.6% growth rate in the previous quarter.    Household borrowing increased at an 8.6% annual rate in the first quarter, compared with 8.9% in the fourth quarter. Borrowing by nonfinancial businesses grew at a 6.4% pace, compared with 12.4% in the fourth quarter. And borrowing by state and local governments was up at a 5.3% pace, compared with 5.8% in the previous quarter.    The figures are adjusted for usual seasonal fluctuations. </TEXT></DOC>